<h3 id=3D"advanced_algorithms" class=3D"wp-block-heading">Advanced algorith=
ms<a href=3D"https://developer.nvidia.com/blog/model-quantization-concepts-=
methods-and-why-it-matters/#advanced_algorithms" aria-label=3D"Scroll to Ad=
vanced algorithms section" class=3D"heading-anchor-link"><i class=3D"fas fa=
-link"></i></a></h3>



<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">Beyond the basic AbsMax algorithm, several =
advanced quantization algorithms have emerged to enhance efficiency while m=
inimizing degradation in accuracy. This section briefly introduces three of=
 the most widely adopted.</p>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li><a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2306.00978" data-wpel-link=3D"exclude"=
>Activation-aware Weight Quantization (AWQ)</a>: AWQ is a weight-only quant=
ization method that identifies and protects a small fraction of =E2=80=9Csa=
lient=E2=80=9D weight channels=E2=80=94those most critical to model perform=
ance=E2=80=94by analyzing activation statistics collected during calibratio=
n. It applies per-channel scaling to these important weights, effectively r=
educing quantization error and enabling efficient low-bit quantization.</li=
>



<li>Generative Pre-trained Transformer Quantization (<a href=3D"https://arx=
iv.org/abs/2210.17323" data-wpel-link=3D"exclude">GPTQ</a>): GPTQ compresse=
s models by quantizing each row of a weight matrix independently. It uses a=
pproximate second-order information, specifically the Hessian matrix, to gu=
ide the quantization process. This approach minimizes the output error intr=
oduced by quantization, enabling efficient and accurate compression with mi=
nimal loss in model performance.</li>



<li><a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2211.10438" data-wpel-link=3D"exclude"=
>SmoothQuant</a>:&nbsp; SmoothQuant enables both weights and activations to=
 be quantized to 8 bits by applying a mathematically equivalent per-channel=
 scaling transformation that smooths out activation outliers, shifting quan=
tization difficulty from activations to weights and preserving model accura=
cy and hardware efficiency.</li>
</ul>



<h2 id=3D"quantization_approaches" class=3D"wp-block-heading">Quantization =
approaches<a href=3D"https://developer.nvidia.com/blog/model-quantization-c=
oncepts-methods-and-why-it-matters/#quantization_approaches" aria-label=3D"=
Scroll to Quantization approaches section" class=3D"heading-anchor-link"><i=
 class=3D"fas fa-link"></i></a></h2>



<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">Quantizing a model=E2=80=99s weights is str=
aightforward, as these are static and data independent, with no additional =
data needed in most cases. Unlike weights, activations dynamically depend o=
n input data distributions that can vary significantly across different inp=
uts and thereby influence the ideal scaling factor. Doing this calibration =
on pre-trained models refers to post-training quantization (PTQ).</p>



<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">During PTQ we add observers to each activat=
ion we want to quantize and inference the model with representative data. T=
he observers then look at the activation output and use the same algorithm =
as before to determine a scaling factor. In AbsMax-quantization, the maximu=
m absolute activation value <mjx-container class=3D"MathJax CtxtMenu_Attach=
